as the notion that a new body is something you can buy or that appearance changes your life. Flesh Wounds is an inquiry into the ideas and practices that have forged such a culture. Tying the boom in cosmetic surgery to a culture-wide trend toward celebrity, Blum explores our growing compulsion to emulate what remain for most of us two-dimensional icons. Moving between personal experiences and observations, interviews with patients and surgeons, and readings of literature and cultural moments, her book reveals the ways in which the practice of cosmetic surgery captures the condition of identity in contemporary culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSurgery, PlasticxPsychological aspects. 0aSurgery, PlasticxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aamerican culture.  aamerican identity.  aanthropology.  abeauty icons.  abeauty ideals.  acelebrity.  acontemporary culture.  acosmetic surgery.  acultural analysis.  acultural criticism.  acultural practices.  aelective surgery.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  afeminism.  agender studies.  ainterviews.  amodern society.  anonfiction account.  apatients and doctors.  aphilosophical.  aplastic surgeons.  aplastic surgery.  apsychology.  asocial conditions.  asociology.  ayouthful ideals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021723240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093873140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938731423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938731/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY